  "description": [
    "r jr VOL XXVII No 50 Washington D C I L N S How trade unions endeavor to meet the problem of unemployment among their members is told by the Bureau of Labor Statistics United States department of labor in a re port entitled American Trade Unions and the Problem of Unemployment Trade unions seek to provide jobs for their members by limiting their membership by insisting upon equal division of work among the regular workers and by helping the workers who have lost their job to find another the report says Union Does Best to Help When a union member finds him self out of a job he can rely upon his union to do its best to find another says the report which continues Few international unions maintain regular employment offices but there is hardly a local which does not have some person in touch with conditions and opportunities in the trade In some cases also a regular office is maintained whose sole business it is to find work for its jobless members Many unions indeed specify in their agreements with the employers that the latter must apply to the union for men to fill any labor requirements"
  ],
